[3] Northwestern Europe
Date: Thu 23 Aug 2007
From: Sabine Zentis <CVLonghorns@aol.com>
The last days saw a dramatic increase in numbers of bluetongue
(BTV-8) cases notified to the authorities in Western Europe.
Updated information can be found at the following URLs:
For Belgium:
<http://www.favv-afsca.fgov.be/crisis/sa-blueT/doc07/2007-08-22-KAART_v13.pdf>,
For Germany:
<http://www.bmelv.de/cln_044/nn_753008/DE/07-SchutzderTiere/Tierseuchen/Blauzungenkrankheit/__Blauzungenkrankheit__node.html__nnn=true>.
In addition, information provided by affected countries at today's
[23 Aug 2007] SCFCAH meeting are available from the EU website:
<http://ec.europa.eu/food/committees/regulatory/scfcah/animal_health/index_en.htm>,
[from where presentations from Luxembourg, Belgium, the Netherlands
and France are available on line - Mod.AS].
--
Sabine Zentis
Castleview Pedigree English Longhorns
Gut Laach
52385 Nideggen
Germany
<CVLonghorns@aol.com>
[There is a clear deterioration of the situation during 2007 in all 5
affected northwestern European countries compared to 2006. According
to unofficial information from a reliable source, farmers in
northwestern Germany are devastated, as the virus is virtually
sweeping the countryside. The situation in the Netherlands and
Belgium is equally grim.
As long as a safe, efficacious BTV-8 vaccine remains unavailable,
there is not much to be done to diminish losses in susceptible sheep.
Symptomatic treatment of sick animals can be attempted; breeders may
be advised to protect BT-infected animals from solar radiation, known
empirically to have adverse clinical effects. - Mod.AS]
